<paragraph blockId="1.[264,1324,1116,1902]" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">
Diagnosis.­ Members of the subgenus 
<taxonomicName box="[737,923,1116,1141]" class="Insecta" family="Agromyzidae" genus="Xenophytomyza" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[737,923,1116,1141]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">Xenophytomyza</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished from other subgenera of 
<taxonomicName box="[421,560,1156,1181]" class="Insecta" family="Agromyzidae" genus="Cerodontha" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[421,560,1156,1181]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">Cerodontha</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by their angulate first flagellomere, the presence of only one pair of scutellar bristles, mostly or entirely brownish­black body and by the distal tubules of the phallus which are fused or partly fused (
<figureCitation box="[755,841,1236,1262]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 3" captionStartId="3.[264,382,1412,1436]" captionTargetBox="[273,1310,604,1388]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[270,1318,604,1398]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 3. Cerodontha (Xenophytomyza) biseta (Hendel). 1, phallus lateral view (Jamaica, LEM); 2, phallus ventral view (Jamaica, LEM); 3, wing showing infuscation at junction between C and R 1. FIGURES 4 ­ 6. Cerodontha (Xenophytomyza) illinoensis (Malloch). 4, phallus lateral view (White Heath, IL, specimen  12252, INHS); 5, phallus lateral view, variation (White Heath, IL, specimen  12253, INHS); 6, phallus ventral view (White Heath, IL, specimen  12253, INHS)" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/157067/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">Figs. 2</figureCitation>
, 6). The closely related subgenus 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Agromyzidae" genus="Cerodontha" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" sensu="stricto">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">Cerodontha</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[353,391,1276,1302]" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" sensu="stricto">s.s.</taxonomicNameLabel>
also has only one pair of scutellar bristles, the first flagellomere is angulate (or with a spine at the anterodorsal corner) and some species have the distal tubules of the phallus fused or partly fused, but they always have more extensive yellow on the body (
<bibRefCitation author="Boucher" box="[272,444,1396,1422]" pageId="1" pageNumber="8" refString="Boucher, S. (2002) Revision of Nearctic species of Cerodontha (Cerodontha) (Diptera: Agromyzidae). The Canadian Entomologist, 134, 577 - 603." type="journal article" year="2002">
Boucher 
<number box="[380,444,1396,1422]" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" value="2002.0">2002</number>
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[264,1324,1116,1902]" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">
Distribution.­ 
<taxonomicName box="[479,665,1436,1461]" class="Insecta" family="Agromyzidae" genus="Xenophytomyza" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[479,665,1436,1461]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">Xenophytomyza</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is almost exclusively Holarctic. The Palearctic species have a boreal­montane distribution. Most European species occur in the nemoral zone, broad­leaved transitional forest between boreal forest and steppe. The eastern Palearctic species are more often associated with boreal forest, while the middle Asian species are exclusively found at high elevations (V.V. Zlobin, pers. comm.). In the Nearctic, however, 
<taxonomicName box="[264,450,1636,1661]" class="Insecta" family="Agromyzidae" genus="Xenophytomyza" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[264,450,1636,1661]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">Xenophytomyza</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species occur mainly in lowland areas, often in mesic grasslands and disturbed habitats, including forest paths, public parks and roadsides.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[264,1324,1116,1902]" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">
Host plants.­ As far as is known, all 
<taxonomicName box="[737,876,1716,1741]" class="Insecta" family="Agromyzidae" genus="Cerodontha" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[737,876,1716,1741]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">Cerodontha</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species are miners on Monocotyledoneae. Only three species of 
<taxonomicName box="[613,799,1756,1781]" class="Insecta" family="Agromyzidae" genus="Xenophytomyza" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[613,799,1756,1781]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">Xenophytomyza</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have known host plants, all in the family 
<taxonomicName box="[264,360,1796,1822]" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Poaceae</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Tschirnhaus" box="[375,586,1796,1822]" pageId="1" pageNumber="8" refString="Tschirnhaus, M. von. (1991) New results on the ecology, morphology, and systematics of Agromyzidae (Diptera). In: Weismann, L, Orszagh I. &amp; Pont, A. C. (Ed) Proceedings of the Second International Congress of Dipterology, SPB Academic Publishing, The Hague, pp. 285 - 313." type="book chapter" year="1991">
Tschirnhaus 
<number box="[525,586,1796,1822]" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" value="1991.0">1991</number>
</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Zlobin" box="[599,747,1796,1822]" pageId="1" pageNumber="8" refString="Zlobin, V. V. (1993) Review of mining flies of the genus Cerodontha Rond. (Diptera: Agromyzidae) VI. Subgenus Xenophytomyza Frey. Proceedings of the Zoological Institute, Russian Academy of Sciences, 251, 135 - 156. [In Russian.]" type="book chapter" year="1993">
Zlobin 
<number box="[684,747,1796,1822]" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" value="1993.0">1993</number>
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[264,1324,1116,1902]" lastBlockId="2.[264,1324,284,750]" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="3" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">
Remarks.­ All species in the subgenera 
<taxonomicName box="[775,961,1836,1861]" class="Insecta" family="Agromyzidae" genus="Xenophytomyza" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[775,961,1836,1861]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">Xenophytomyza</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[1017,1156,1836,1861]" class="Insecta" family="Agromyzidae" genus="Cerodontha" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1017,1156,1836,1861]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">Cerodontha</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
lack the basal scutellar bristles present in other 
<taxonomicName box="[652,815,1876,1902]" class="Insecta" family="Agromyzidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Agromyzidae</taxonomicName>
; the absence of these bristles is an apomorphy that supports a sister group relationship between these two subgenera. However, so far there are no well­supported apomorphic characters defining each of these subgenera. The absence of the funnel (“Trichter”) at the tip of the phallus used by 
<bibRefCitation author="Nowakowski" box="[1052,1293,364,390]" pageId="2" pageNumber="8" refString="Nowakowski J. T. (1973) Monographie der europaischen Arten der Gattung Cerodontha Rond. (Diptera: Agromyzidae). Annales Zoologici, 31, 1 - 327." type="journal article" year="1973">
Nowakowski (
<number box="[1223,1284,364,390]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" value="1973.0">1973</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
to characterize 
<taxonomicName box="[414,600,404,429]" class="Insecta" family="Agromyzidae" genus="Xenophytomyza" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[414,600,404,429]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Xenophytomyza</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(in addition to the form of the first flagellomere and the dark colour) is not a valid character, since the structure is present in 
<taxonomicName authority="Zlobin 1993" authorityName="Zlobin" authorityYear="1993" class="Insecta" family="Agromyzidae" genus="Cerodontha" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="biseta" subGenus="Xenophytomyza">
<emphasis box="[1058,1085,444,469]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">C.</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[1106,1223,444,469]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">X.) biseta</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Zlobin" pageId="2" pageNumber="8" refString="Zlobin, V. V. (1993) Review of mining flies of the genus Cerodontha Rond. (Diptera: Agromyzidae) VI. Subgenus Xenophytomyza Frey. Proceedings of the Zoological Institute, Russian Academy of Sciences, 251, 135 - 156. [In Russian.]" type="book chapter" year="1993">
Zlobin 
<number box="[264,327,484,510]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" value="1993.0">1993</number>
</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
. 
<bibRefCitation author="Dempewolf" box="[350,577,484,510]" pageId="2" pageNumber="8" refString="Dempewolf, M. (2001) Larvalmorphologie und Phylogenie der Agromyzidae (Diptera). Unpublished PhD dissertation, Universitat Bielefeld. 256 pp." type="book" year="2001">
Dempewolf (
<number box="[508,569,484,510]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" value="2001.0">2001</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
found no apomorphies to separate exemplar species of 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Agromyzidae" genus="Cerodontha" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" sensu="stricto">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Cerodontha</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[355,418,524,550]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" sensu="stricto">s. str.</taxonomicNameLabel>
(
<taxonomicName authority="Nowakowski" authorityName="Nowakowski" box="[438,727,524,550]" class="Insecta" family="Agromyzidae" genus="Cerodontha" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hennigi">
<emphasis box="[438,563,524,549]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">C. hennigi</emphasis>
Nowakowski
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Panzer" authorityName="Panzer" box="[788,1075,524,550]" class="Insecta" family="Agromyzidae" genus="Cerodontha" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="denticornis">
<emphasis box="[788,957,524,549]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">C. denticornis</emphasis>
(Panzer))
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Agromyzidae" genus="Xenophytomyza" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="venturii">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Xenophytomyza venturii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Species­level relationships within this monophyletic group are not well­resolved and it is not yet known whether each of the two subgenera is monophyletic. A final decision on the status of these two subgenera will require a phylogenetic analysis of all included species. Published records of 
<taxonomicName box="[726,912,684,709]" class="Insecta" family="Agromyzidae" genus="Xenophytomyza" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[726,912,684,709]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Xenophytomyza</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species with weak basal scutellars refer to a species now assigned to the subgenus 
<emphasis box="[825,931,724,749]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Poemyza</emphasis>
Hendel (
<bibRefCitation author="Zlobin" box="[1038,1189,724,750]" pageId="2" pageNumber="8" refString="Zlobin, V. V. (2001) Review of mining flies of the genus Cerodontha Rondani. XI. Some remarks on the Oriental Poemyza species (Diptera: Agromyzidae). International Journal of Dipterological Research, 12, 107 - 112." type="book chapter" year="2001">
Zlobin 
<number box="[1126,1189,724,750]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" value="2001.0">2001</number>
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
